```
Cypress will start and run the tests. If any of the tests fail, Cypress will capture a screenshot of the failure and save it to the `/cypress/screenshots` directory. The images will be named based on the test name and timestamp.

You can also customize the screenshot naming convention by specifying a custom filename in the `CYPRESS_screenshotNamePattern` environment variable.

**Tips and Variations**

* To run specific tests or a test suite, use the `--spec` flag when running `docker-compose up`, for example: `docker-compose up --spec cypress/integration/example.spec.js`
* To customize the screenshot directory, set the `CYPRESS_screenshotDir` environment variable in the `docker-compose.yml` file, for example: `CYPRESS_screenshotDir=/path/to/screenshots`
* To disable screenshot capture for specific tests or test suites, set `CYPRESS_screenshotOnRun` to `false` in the test or test suite configuration.

This setup provides a solid foundation for your Cypress testing framework, leveraging Docker for a portable and reproducible environment and image snapshotting for easy debugging and visual verification.

Here is a simple implementation of a function that converts markdown to HTML. This function uses a third-party library called `pugiconv` to do the conversion.

Please note that this is a basic implementation and doesn't support all markdown features. You may need to add more functionality based on your specific requirements.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <pugiconv.h>
#include <iostream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_node root = doc.append_child(pugi::node_type::node_element, "html");
    root.append_child(pugi::node_type::node_element, "body").append_child(pugi::node_type::node_pcdata).set_value(markdown.c_str());

    std::stringstream html;
    pugi::xml_writer_settings<char> settings('\t', ' ', 0, 0);
    doc.save_html(html, settings);

    return html.str();
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Hello **bold** and [link](https://example.com)";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```
